ld, and the creation of networks that link the afflicted, their kin, and their healers are all central to ngoma—and familiar to Western self-help institutions as well. Students of African healing and also those interested in the comparative and historical study of medicine, religion, and music will find Ngoma a valuable and thought-provoking book.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHealingzAfrica, Central. 0aHealingzAfrica, Southern. 0aRites and ceremonieszAfrica, Central. 0aRites and ceremonieszAfrica, Southern. 0aTraditional medicinezAfrica, Central. 0aTraditional medicinezAfrica, Southern. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aafrica.  aafrican studies.  aanthropology.  abantu.  abone throwing.  acapetown.  acentral africa.  adance.  adar es salaam.  adisease.  adivination.  adrum.  aethnography.  afolk belief.  afolk medicine.  afolklore.  ahealers.  ahealing cults.  ahealing.  aillness.  akinshasa.  akinship.  ambabane.  amedicine.  amusic.  angoma.  anonfiction.  aperformance.  aperforming arts.  apossession.  areligion.  arite.  aritual healing.  asocial science.  asociology.  asong.  asouth africa.  asouthern africa.  aspirits.  atradition.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z978311063534840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091085040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520910850423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520910850/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY